g.aria-label: " The figure Below shows a speaker placed at the open end of a tube. The speaker emits sound at a constant wavelength , and forms a standing wave inside the tube. The length of the entire tube is = . The center of the tube contains a stack of thin metal plates (oriented parallel to the x-z axis) placed closely together. The ends of each plate, at A and B, are connected (via heat exchangers) to heat reservoirs RH and RC maintained at temperature TH and TC respectively."
- In experiment 1, heat is transferred from RC to RH. - In experiment 2, there is no heat transfer between the reservoirs. - In experiment 3, heat is transferred from RH to RC .

"Note that: (i) During each experiment, the corresponding temperature gradient along the metal plates remains constant. (ii) The distance between two adjacent plates is such that heat transfer between the air and the plate occurs instantaneously. (iii) The heat capacity of the metal plates is extremely large. (iv) The viscosity of the gas is negligible. (v) The length of the metal plate is very small as compared to the length of the tube. (vi) The metal plates and the heat exchangers do not disrupt the wave-fronts or the flow of air. Using this set-up, three different experiments are conducted. In each experiment we maintain a temperature gradient along all the metal plates as shown in the Fig. 2 and measures the heat transfer between the two reservoirs."
In all cases, the initial temperature (when the speaker is off) of the gas between the metal plates is equal to the temperature of the local region of the plate adjacent to the gas.
Using this set-up, Atharva performs three different experiments.
